english:
  title: Verses Presented at the Lantern Festival Offering of Immortal Peaches, Spoken by the Court Dancers
  author: Choe Ja
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the fifteenth night, we gaze upon the lanterns—
    Across the divine realm, red lotus petals scatter like ten thousand measures,
    Fruit that ripens but once in a thousand years:
    Seven jade peaches, gifts from the Mother of Immortals.

    With reverence we consider: Our Sovereign inherits
    The frugality and diligence of Emperor Yu,
    And ascends to the holiness and respect of Emperor Tang.
    The court shines with clarity, unblemished by fault—
    Already peaceful, and peaceful still.
    When the kingdom finds leisure, it celebrates with joy.
    The eight musical tones harmonize without discord,
    A hundred entertainments unfold without cease.
    This auspicious lantern spectacle renews itself,
    As jubilant voices rise in chorus.

    We, ashamed of our humble talents, presume
    To appear among the dancers of the court.
    The phoenix, stirred by the melodies of Shun, dances gracefully
    Into the palace hall;
    The crane, from the blessed islands, comes solemnly
    To sing by the celestial pool.

    We offer these verses:

    Between clouds of five colors, lords and ministers feast,
    And the newly plucked peach glistens with morning dew, its fragrance pure.
    Though aged through immortal eons, its flesh remains jade-green,
    Now flushed with the rosy warmth of imperial grace upon one cheek.
    Why should wind and rain hasten the golden ripening?
    Heaven and earth care not for the plucking of precious blooms.
    Even a single stolen taste grants a thousand years of life—
    What need to speak of these, heaped full upon the serving tray?
  footnotes:
    - The 'fifteen night' refers to the full moon celebration, traditionally a time of lantern festivals in East Asia.
    - Emperor Yu and Emperor Tang are legendary sage-kings of ancient China, representing virtue and good governance.
    - The 'eight musical tones' (八音) refer to the eight types of musical instruments in traditional Chinese music theory.
    - The phoenix and crane are symbols of auspiciousness and longevity in East Asian mythology.
    - The 'peach of immortality' is a reference to the Queen Mother of the West's magical peaches that grant eternal life, a common motif in Chinese mythology.
    - The reference to 'a single stolen taste' alludes to the story of Dongfang Shuo, a legendary immortal who stole a peach from the Queen Mother of the West and gained immortality.
